Comment:
Keen for the film regardless but hot take on Shuri and why recasting it may have been a better option‚Ä¶ 
Looking at it from a kids perspective‚Ä¶most of marvel is white, we can all agree on that. Young boys have grown up with these super heroes as people they idolize and see themselves being, where it being playing around at school or they literally look like a young avenger type kid.
Black Panther was the first POC as a hero in the MCU, young black kids (boys) finally have someone they can look to and a character they can idolize and have only seen one film with their hero in it (not counting Civil War or Infinity War & Endgame). By making it Shuri, yes, it‚Äôs great that now black girls can idolize someone, but the young boys now have no one to look up to. And the fairness is just moot. 
A strategy to pair both may be to have recast him, and then have Shuri be trained to be the next BP for the third film therefore keeping all the kids happy!

Comment: ¬†@suzie55¬† we Americans mention classification ( Negroid, Caucasoid, Mongoloid) because our lives and history here in America has been shaped by such classifications. Our classification is extremely similar to Apartheid that was represented in SA. So yes we represent our race classification, ( simplified as black in America/ scientifically Negroid) but not necessarily skin color. We only mention skin color to distinguish others amongst ourselves.  And we also aren't the only people that mention color. Most civilizations have a caste system whether they admit it or not. Darker individuals are assumed to be lower class workers because darker skin meant sun exposure, which in turn is equated to manual labor. Lighter skin meant no sun exposure hence no manual labor, pampered and privileged.  Examples of cultures who value caste: India, China, Japan, Korea, Spain, Mexico, Nigeria, Sudan, Italy...You get the picture. India currently has the highest market for skin bleaching in the world. Surprisingly, America's market for bleaching is minimal. (Not non existent) Now since I got that out of the way, congratulations on your nation being represented! Comment:
Is kind of neat looking for sure, I doubt that's his standard flight method though. Dude can reach escape velocity. You'd have to be flying in a straight line for that. 
Namor was the first character in comic books who had the power of flight. It was his mutant gift. It's been theorized that he flies using telekinesis, and uses the ankle wings to steer. Though supposedly there are some comics where his wings were damaged and he was unable to fly.

Really curious to see how they treat him in the MCU as he's kind of ridiculous on the ability scales. One of the strongest characters in Marvel comics. Insane durability (like comparable to The Thing and Collosus). High speed flight agile enough to dodge shots from military jets. Enhanced healing, senses, and stamina. Fast enough to dodge surveillance cameras. Hydrokinesis. I do think, as others have stated, that they're going to merge him into the on-going narrative of different gods in the Marvel universe having avatars.

Comment: Thank you all. I think the film addresses grief really elegantly. The dialogues are simple but have so much depth. I found Shuri's struggle in particular really relatable. Losing the people you love most can make you so angry - even more so when you felt like you were supposed to do things for them but never managed to. I don't like the person I am at times at the moment. I hope, in time, I can be as courageous as her in honouring my mother's memory and being a good person and still go on to do things that would be worthy of her own life, struggle, and sacrifice. Right now I struggle to do anything, I'm so broken.
author: @SehajSingh94

Comment: ¬†@raynefelix2775¬† the world is split up into people who don't and don't understand true loss and grief. This is the first film I've seen where grief feels like a real thing. Not just having characters die and then other get over it and find themselves, but actually addressing how one can lose themselves in grief. Maybe that's just because I'm finally going through it myself though. I'm so sorry for your loss. The world should know every little detail of your beautiful mother for she IS the world to you, just as mine is to me. I'm so sorry much of the world will never understand that. I hope you can find a way to still live a meaningful and beautiful life, something I'm struggling immensely to do so myself.
author: @SehajSingh94

Comment:
1 year old!

As a follow-up to the highest grossing superhero film with an African American lead this was a nice send off for the late Chadwick Boseman 
Loved as Dominique Thorne as Riri Williams/Ironheart utilizing her MIT college degree in Stark-like technology not knowing the device she made was in the hands of the CIA 
Definitely liked what they did with Namor making him Latino-centric and recontextualizing him; he‚Äôs part of a hidden nation much like Wakanda but having to deal with colonizers like the Spanish Conquistadors actually enslaving locals 
His background is influenced mostly by Mesoamerican culture speaking a lot of Mayan dialect 
Shuri has a duty to carry on the science to keep her country strong since it didn‚Äôt save her brother dying from an unknown illness 
This didn't need to be 2 hours and 41 min long; the first 40 min is kinda sluggish and it takes forever for Shuri to actually put on the suit 
She rejects religion and tradition and has to learn how to not let vengeance consume you much like it did T‚ÄôChalla 
She is the most self-destructive out of the bunch not being able to grieve 
Everett Ross barely has anything to do but try to convince the CIA that Wakanda shouldn‚Äôt be disbanded and easily labeled the enemy 
But this shows how a nation responds to hostility when constantly begging for resources and weaponry and when negotiation fails 
Any nation can still have allies but war is the last resort when vengeance consumes given every horrific tragedy that's happened in human history whether it‚Äôs slavery, genocide or being wiped out by disease 
The first movie was way more fun and this kinda strains from having too many characters in here messing with the flow 
But Wakanda remains a character in itself much like its inhabitants 
There‚Äôs themes of dealing with loss and mourning 
It's not a nation in a poor country that's the enemy maybe it's everyone else 
There‚Äôs also the mother-daughter relationship being maintained here much like the father-son dynamic in the original film 
Angela Bassett gives one surefire of a performance of a mother lingering among who‚Äôs already been lost and running out of options 
We have a lot of pain and danger and rage after suffering through something like covid similar to these Wakandans going through what Thanos did 
Acts more of a geo political thriller and with a nation coming from the bleakness of loss to a stable place from which a new generation can move forward 
This movie is a darker and more emotional approach than most MCU films but acts as a respectable book end to a late actor

Comment:
I dont know why the reviews arent that grade. This has to be one of my favourite mcu movie. It's right there along with guardians of galaxy vol1. And I think this might just be my favourite mcu movie. I like that the main character shuri is so full of vengeance, but not exactly in an anti hero kind of way, but you can feel the pain of her only not too long ago mourning the death of her beloved brother and then her mother, and even though we can guess pretty well how itll end up, at the moment when she was so blinded by that rage, the emotion really got through to the audience, unlike any of the other movies. But because that emotion felt so raw, I still feel worry that shed make the wrong choice and consumed by her grief and rage. 
What I didnt like was pop songs being used  in the movie, or songs with actual lyrics. I thought the whole movie could really do without it. I thought the score and the sound effect is also on another level compared to the other mcu movies but its probably just me.

Comment:
Overall thoughts: the movie was good, but not as great as the first.

I had mixed feelings about Prince Namor's origins being changed in the film. In the comics, Namor was the son of a Sea Captain and an Atlantean Princess. However in the movie, it was changed as to separate itself from DCEU's and DC Comics Aquaman, since their origins are similar. Most likely done for the fact that people never read the comics and would rather watch the movie instead. Good thing that they kept Namor as an anti-hero like he is in the comics. He could be a good guy or a bad guy, but it all depends on the plot.

I expected the ending to tease the audience with an appearance of Kasper Cole, who becomes the next Black Panther after Killmonger in the comics. Better yet, Killmonger being resurrected by Madam Slay at the end and becoming the next Black Panther before Kasper Kole takes the role.

8 out of 10. Hopefully Black Panther 3 will feature, as I said before, Kasper Kole aka The White Tiger.

Comment: It's extremely disappointing to sit and watch through this movie. Despite their fictional advances in science and technology, they put little effort into making Shuri/Riri sound intelligent or have basic understanding in of STEM field. They make it seem these two are capable of developing a large scale project at a pace that's not humanly possible. There's a lot of requirements, designing, developing, and testing that creates a quality product yet everything they produce was perfect. The way they try to convey themselves with very minimal jargon and mixing fields together made it very awkward to watch. They seem to be an experts in Medical, then Mechanical and Electrical, then in Machine Learning/Computer Science but there's a broad distinction between each field that would require so much time to learn. These girls are very UNINTELLIGENT for what they are promoting in their story. Differential equations? You can't be serious with me. That is like entry level calculus. Comment:
It was OK at best.  For me the cheap and easy route of simply parasitizing existing works instead of CREATING new works is getting old.  This is a problem that's been ongoing for some time now, not unique to this production.

The entire back story of Prince Namor and the Atlanteans was completely erased, then the name pasted onto someone else's idea pulled out of nowhere.  To give it legitimacy I assume.  Not a great promo for creative writing.

The movie was mildly entertaining.  The acting wasn't awful.  The Queen played the part to a "T", but everything else was just sort of "Meh" to me.  Mostly because EVERYTHING about Namor and his people in the movie was a case of "cultural appropriation".
